+<body>
+  <header>
+    <h1>Setting Up Git and GitHub: A Step-by-Step Guide</h1>
+    <p>
+      Follow this comprehensive guide to install Visual Studio Code and Git, configure your GitHub account,
+      and master the core Git commands used in everyday development workflows.
+    </p>
+  </header>
+
+  <main>
+    <section>
+      <h2>Why Git and GitHub?</h2>
+      <p>
+        Git is a distributed version control system that tracks changes to your code, while GitHub is a
+        cloud-based hosting service for Git repositories with collaboration features such as pull requests,
+        issue tracking, and project management. Together, they form the backbone of modern software development
+        and collaboration.
+      </p>
+      <blockquote>
+        <strong>Tip:</strong> When people say “push it to GitHub,” they are really describing a workflow that uses
+        Git locally and GitHub as the remote backup and collaboration hub.
+      </blockquote>
+    </section>
+
+    <section>
+      <h2>1. Install Visual Studio Code (Code Editor)</h2>
+      <p>
+        Visual Studio Code (VS Code) is a lightweight yet powerful code editor with built-in Git integration and an
+        extensible marketplace. Installing it is the first step toward a smooth Git workflow.
+      </p>
+      <ol>
+        <li>
+          <strong>Download VS Code:</strong> Visit the
+          <a href="https://code.visualstudio.com/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer">official download page</a> and
+          grab the installer for your operating system.
+        </li>
+        <li>
+          <strong>Run the Installer:</strong> Launch the downloaded installer and follow the prompts. The default
+          configuration is perfect for getting started quickly.
+        </li>
+        <li><strong>Launch VS Code:</strong> Open the editor after installation to ensure everything works.</li>
+        <li>
+          <strong>Optional – Enable Auto Save:</strong> In VS Code, go to <em>File &gt; Auto Save</em> so changes are
+          persisted automatically.
+        </li>
+      </ol>
+      <p>
+        VS Code’s integrated terminal and Source Control panel allow you to execute Git commands and review changes
+        without leaving the editor.
+      </p>
+    </section>
+
+    <section>
+      <h2>2. Install Git (Version Control System)</h2>
+      <p>
+        Git is the engine that records your project history. Install it so you can create repositories, commit changes,
+        and synchronize with GitHub.
+      </p>
+      <ol>
+        <li>
+          <strong>Download Git:</strong> Visit <a href="https://git-scm.com/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer">git-scm.com</a>
+          and download the installer for your operating system.
+        </li>
+        <li><strong>Run the Installer:</strong> Accept the recommended defaults for a worry-free setup.</li>
+        <li><strong>Complete Installation:</strong> Finish the wizard to install Git (and Git Bash on Windows).</li>
+        <li>
+          <strong>Verify Installation:</strong> Open a terminal and run <code>git --version</code> to confirm Git is available.
+        </li>
+      </ol>
+      <p>
+        After installation, configure Git with your identity so commits are correctly attributed:
+      </p>
+      <pre><code>git config --global user.name "Your Name"
+git config --global user.email "you@example.com"</code></pre>
+      <p>
+        Remember: Git runs locally on your machine, while GitHub is the remote service where you’ll store and collaborate on
+        your repositories.
+      </p>
+    </section>
+
+    <section>
+      <h2>3. Create a GitHub Account</h2>
+      <ol>
+        <li>
+          <strong>Sign Up:</strong> Visit <a href="https://github.com/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer">github.com</a>
+          and create an account if you don’t already have one.
+        </li>
+        <li>
+          <strong>Enable Two-Factor Authentication:</strong> Add an extra layer of security with an authenticator app.
+        </li>
+        <li><strong>Log In:</strong> Sign in from your browser or connect VS Code to GitHub for seamless integration.</li>
+      </ol>
+    </section>
+
+    <section>
+      <h2>4. Create a Local Project Folder</h2>
+      <ol>
+        <li><strong>Create a Folder:</strong> Make a new folder where your project files will live.</li>
+        <li><strong>Open in VS Code:</strong> Use <em>File &gt; Open Folder...</em> or run <code>code .</code> from the folder.</li>
+        <li>
+          <strong>Initialize Git:</strong> Open the integrated terminal in VS Code and execute <code>git init</code> to start a
+          repository.
+        </li>
+      </ol>
+      <p>
+        Once Git is initialized, the Source Control panel in VS Code becomes active and tracks your file changes.
+      </p>
+    </section>
+
+    <section>
+      <h2>5. Create a Remote Repository on GitHub</h2>
+      <ol>
+        <li>
+          <strong>Start a New Repo:</strong> Click the <strong>+</strong> icon on GitHub and choose <em>New repository</em>.
+        </li>
+        <li>
+          <strong>Configure Settings:</strong> Name the repository, set visibility, and leave README, .gitignore, and license
+          unchecked.
+        </li>
+        <li>
+          <strong>Create Repository:</strong> GitHub provides the remote URL you’ll connect to your local project.
+        </li>
+      </ol>
+    </section>
+
+    <section>
+      <h2>6. Make the First Commit and Push</h2>
+      <ol>
+        <li><strong>Create README.md:</strong> Add a simple introduction to the project.</li>
+        <li><strong>Stage and Commit:</strong> Use VS Code’s Source Control view or run <code>git add</code> and <code>git commit</code>.</li>
+        <li><strong>Rename Branch:</strong> Ensure your default branch is named <code>main</code> with <code>git branch -M main</code>.</li>
+        <li>
+          <strong>Add the Remote:</strong> <code>git remote add origin https://github.com/YourUsername/YourRepo.git</code>
+        </li>
+        <li><strong>Push to GitHub:</strong> <code>git push -u origin main</code> uploads your commit.</li>
+      </ol>
+      <p>Refresh the GitHub page to confirm that your README and initial commit are visible.</p>
+    </section>
+
+    <section>
+      <h2>7. Ongoing Workflow: Commit and Push</h2>
+      <p>Follow this rhythm whenever you make changes:</p>
+      <ol>
+        <li><strong>Edit Files:</strong> Add or modify project files in VS Code.</li>
+        <li><strong>Stage Changes:</strong> Select the files to include using the Source Control panel or <code>git add</code>.</li>
+        <li><strong>Commit:</strong> Write a descriptive message that explains the change.</li>
+        <li><strong>Push:</strong> Upload your commits to GitHub with <code>git push</code>.</li>
+      </ol>
+      <blockquote>
+        <strong>Best Practice:</strong> Commit early and often. Frequent commits create a clear history and make it easier to
+        undo mistakes.
+      </blockquote>
+    </section>
+
+    <section>
+      <h2>8. Clone the Repository on Another Machine</h2>
+      <ol>
+        <li><strong>Copy the Clone URL:</strong> Click the green <em>Code</em> button on GitHub and copy the HTTPS link.</li>
+        <li><strong>Run git clone:</strong> In the terminal, execute <code>git clone &lt;repository-url&gt;</code>.</li>
+        <li>
+          <strong>Open in VS Code:</strong> Launch the cloned folder in VS Code and continue working just like on the original
+          machine.
+        </li>
+      </ol>
+    </section>
+
+    <section>
+      <h2>9. Pull Updates from GitHub</h2>
+      <p>
+        Keep your local repository synchronized with remote changes by running <code>git pull origin main</code>. Resolve any
+        merge conflicts by editing the affected files, then stage and commit the resolution.
+      </p>
+    </section>
+
+    <section>
+      <h2>10. Essential Git Commands and Tips</h2>
+      <ul>
+        <li><code>git status</code> &mdash; Shows the current state of the working directory and staging area.</li>
+        <li><code>git log</code> &mdash; Lists the commit history. Try <code>git log --oneline --graph</code> for a compact view.</li>
+        <li><code>git branch</code> &mdash; Manage feature branches to isolate work.</li>
+        <li><code>git reset</code> and <code>git revert</code> &mdash; Undo changes safely when mistakes happen.</li>
+        <li>
+          <strong>Commit Messages:</strong> Write clear, concise descriptions so collaborators understand the purpose of each
+          change.
+        </li>
+      </ul>
+    </section>
+
+    <section>
+      <h2>11. Write a Helpful README</h2>
+      <p>
+        Your README introduces the project. Use Markdown to format headings, lists, code, and links. A sample structure might
+        include:
+      </p>
+      <ul>
+        <li>Project title and short description</li>
+        <li>How to install or run the project</li>
+        <li>Features or screenshots</li>
+        <li>Version control notes or acknowledgments</li>
+      </ul>
+      <p>
+        Example Markdown snippet:
+      </p>
+      <pre><code># Project Title
+
+Brief description of the project.
+
+## How to Run
+- Step 1
+- Step 2
+
+## Version Control
+This project uses Git for version control.</code></pre>
+      <p>
+        Update <code>README.md</code>, then stage, commit, and push so the information is visible on GitHub.
+      </p>
+    </section>
+  </main>
+
+  <footer>
+    <p>
